Reworked models

The overall response will be simulated with the following process:

\[ x_{i}(t) = \beta_{k, i}u_{k, i} + (\phi_{m, i}u_{m,i})t + \gamma_{k, i} w_{k, i}(t) + \varepsilon_{i}(t) \tag{1} \]

Where:

  • \(x_{i}(t)\) is the variable of interest (e.g. NDVI) in pixel \(i\);

  • \(u_{k,i}\) is a model matrix of \(k = 1, ..., K\) spatially variable predictors (e.g. landclass);

  • \(w_{m, i}(t)\) are \(m = 1, ..., M\) spatio-temporally variable predictors (e.g. temperature);

  • \(\beta_{k, i}\), \(\phi_{m, i}\), and \(\gamma_{m, i}\) are the effects of the predictors. Each of these can be fixed OR randomly distributed in space \(\{\beta_{k}, \phi_{m}, \gamma_{m} \} \sim N(\mu, \Sigma_\text{Matern})\) (see below); and

  • \(\varepsilon_{i}(t)\) is the spatio-temporally correlated error term.

\(\varepsilon_{i}(t)\) (and \(w_{m,i}\)) is generated with an ARMA process:

\[\varepsilon_{i}(t) = \delta_{i}(t) + \sum_{j = 1}^{p}{\rho_{j}\varepsilon_{i}(t)} + \sum_{j = 1}^{q}{\theta_{j}\varepsilon_{i}(t)} \tag{2}\]

where:

  • \(\sum_{j = 1}^{p}{\rho_{j}\varepsilon_{i}(t)}\) is the AR(p) process;

  • \(\sum_{j = 1}^{q}{\theta_{j}\varepsilon_{i}(t)\) is the MA(q) process; and

  • \(\delta_{i}(t) \sim N(0, \Sigma_{\delta_{i}})\) are spatially correlated errors;

Spatial correlation in the ARMA terms is generated with an exponential power function:

\[\Sigma_{\delta_{i}} = I\eta_i + (\sigma^{2} - \mu_{\eta_i})exp{(-d_{i, j}/r)^a} \tag{3}\]

where:

  • \(I\eta_{i}\) is an Identity matrix multiplied by the nugget \(\eta_{i}\), which may be fixed OR variable in space: \(\eta_{i} \sim N(0, \Sigma_{\text{Matern}})\);

  • \(\sigma^2\) is the sill (variance) of \(\delta_i\) (I’ll stick with unit variance);

  • \(d_{i, j}\) is the distance between pixels \(i\) and \(j\);

  • \(r\) is the range of the spatial auto-correlation (in pixels); and

  • \(a\) is the shape parameter for the auto-correlation function

Other spatial correlations \(\Sigma_{\text{Matern}} = R(h)\) will be generated the Matern Cross-covariance function:

\[R(d_{i, j}; v, c) = 2^{1-v} \Gamma(v)^{-1}(c||d_{i, j}||)^{v} K_{v}(c||d_{i, j}||) \tag{4}\] where :

  • \(c > 0\) is the scale parameter (similar to range \(r\))

  • \(v > 0\) is the smoothness parameter. When \(v = \frac{1}{2}\), \(R(h)\) is equivalent to \(exp(d_{i, j} / c)\) and \(\lim_{v \to \infty} R(h) = exp(-d/2c)^2\)

  • \(\Gamma\) is the gamma function, and

  • \(K\) is a modified Bessel function of the second kind

Note: In practice, this function is very useful for generating smooth spatial correlations and waves (see \(\S\) “Spatially variable parameter” below). But may need some help understanding the math and what it’s actually doing! It may be worth while to also generate \(\delta_{i}\) with Matern correlations?

Simulation Plans

Data Generation

In order to vigorously test the robustness of the PARTS method, we will simulate 1000 sets of predictor variables \(u_{k,i}\) and \(w_{m,j}\) and varying the effects that each of those sets have on \(x_i(t)\). Therfore, \(x\) will be simulated \(1000\) for each unique set of effect parameter combinations. The map for all simulations will be the same size: \(20\times20\) pixels (or some other size, dependant on speed). \(d_{i, j}\) will contain the Euclidean distance between points and will be constant throughout the simulations.

\(u\) will represent land cover class designations, with 4 levels (\(m = 4\)), coded as dummy variables (i.e. \(\{0, 1\}\)). It will be generating by discretizing (by quartiles) a continuous variable produced with the Matern covariance function. \(c\) and \(v\) will be selected to generate a desired spatial pattern and will be constant throughout the simulations. \(u\) will have no nugget and unit variance (i.e. \(\eta = 0\), \(\sigma^2 = 1\)).

\(w\) will be a single (\(k = 1\)) spatio-temporal variable representing temperature. It will be generated as an ARMA(1, 1) model with Matern covariance structure. \(c\) and \(v\) will be selected to generate a desired spatial pattern (different from \(u\)) and will be constant throughout the simulations. \(\rho\) and \(\theta\) will also be predetermined and constant. \(w\) will have unit variance. \(w\) will have no nugget and unit variance (i.e. \(\eta = 0\), \(\sigma^2 = 1\)).

\(x\) will then be generated, for 30 time points (\(t = 1, ..., 30\)), by varying the following parameters on each of the 1000 data sets. This will allow us to compare the effect of the parameter independent of the specific predictor values.

Effects parameters \(\beta\), \(\phi\), and \(\gamma\), will take on one of 3 levels: 2 fixed values (i.e. \(\{0, 0.5\}\)) and one spatially distributed random variable (i.e. \(\sim N(0.5, \Sigma_{\text{Matern}})\)). The AR parameter \(\rho\) will also have 2 levels (e.g. \(\{\rho_1 = .6, \rho_2 = .3\}\) and \(\{\rho_1 = .8, \rho_2 = .1\}\)), the MA parameter \(\theta\) will have 2 levels (e.g \(\{.1, .5\}\)), the spatial nugget \(\eta\) will have 2 levels (i.e. \(\{0, 0.5\}\)), and the spatial correlation range parameter \(r\) will have 2 levels (i.e. \(\{0.2, 0.5\}\)). The spatial correlation shape parameter \(a = 2\) will remain constant througout the simulations.

With this specification there are 432 unique parameter combinations which would yield 432,000 simulations of \(x\). It may be best to also hold \(\beta\) constant or at least restrict it to 2 fixed values, since we aren’t actually interested in our estimate of an the intercept parameter. Doing so would reduce the total simulations to 72,000. It may also be acceptable to hold \(\theta\) constant, further reducing the total to 36,000 simulations. But, we may also decide to add a level of \(\eta\) that is spatially variable.

Model Fitting

For each simulation of \(x\), we will apply the PARTS method. We will use AR_REML to fit a time series to each pixel and then will fit a GLS to slope parameters for the effect of time. We will then compare the overall estimate of the effect of time to the true values \((\phi_{m, i})\). If \(\phi_m\) was spatially variable, we will compare to the mean \(\phi_m\). We will also estimate type I error rates for the case when \(\bar{\beta_m} = \bar{\phi_m} = \bar{\gamma_k} = 0\).

Example Code

This is some code I ran to test out the spatial correlation functions

First we’ll set the initial parameters:

#---
## Initial Parameters
#---

set.seed(3654)

# Sim pars ----
burn.in = 0
sim.iters = 1

# Map pars ----
map.cols = 20
map.rows = 10
npix = map.rows * map.cols # should be a square

# ARMA pars ----
rhos = c(0.6, 0.2)# AR parameter(s): must sum to less than 1
thetas = c(.4) # MA parameter: must be less than 1

# Temporal pars ----
ntime = 30 # number of time points

# varcov pars ----
cormod = "stable" # 'stable' correlation model: varcov = nug+sill*exp(-(d/scale)^shape)
dist.meth = "Eucl" # Euclidean distance
sill = 1 # sill (variance)
r = .25 # range of spatial autocor, relative to width of map (scale parameter)
a = 1 # shape of spatial autocor function (shape parameter)
nug = .2 # fixed nugget

# spatial nugget pars ----
nug.cormod = "matern"
nug.distmeth = "Eucl"
nug.r = .2
nug.s = 20
constrain.nug = c(0, 1) # constrain the spatial nugget to these values

# effect parameters ----
beta = .2 # spatial predictors
phi = .2 # spatio-temporal predictors
gamma = .5 # time trends

# Additinal parameter calculations ----

## Assign coordinates to pixels
coords = as.matrix(expand.grid(x = as.double(1:map.cols), 
                               y = as.double(1:map.rows)))

## spatial correlation
psill = sill - nug # partial sill: if nug is spatially variable, use mean(nug)
range = r * map.cols # range in pixels

## spatially variable parameters
nug.range = nug.r * map.cols
nug.smooth = nug.s


# Sanity checks ----
stopifnot(sum(rhos) < 1)
stopifnot(nrow(coords) == npix)

# parameter table ----

fixed.pars = expand.grid(range = range, a = a, nug = nug, fixed.pars = TRUE)


corpars = list(scale = range, power = a, # parameter list for Covmatrix()
               sill = psill, nugget = nug, mean = 0)
nugpars = list(scale = nug.range, smooth = nug.smooth, 
               mean = 0, sill = 1, nugget = 0)

Then:

  1. Calculate the spatial covariance matrix \(\Sigma_{\delta_{i}}\) with the function Covmatrix from package CompRandFld.
start.time = Sys.time()

# Calculate varcov matrix (Sigma) ----
## Covmatrix() - easier to modify specs
covmat = CompRandFld::Covmatrix(coordx = coords, 
                                 distance = dist.meth,
                                 corrmodel = cormod,
                                 param = corpars)$covmatrix
# invcholV = remotePARTS::invert_chol(covmat)

# ## Tony's
# d = as.matrix(stats::dist(coords, method = "euc"))
# d.scale = (d - min(d)) / (max(d) - min(d)) # rescale to (0, 1)
# covmat2 = diag(rep(nug, npix)) + (1 - nug) * exp(-(d/r)^a)
# invcholV2 = remotePARTS::invert_chol(covmat2)
# ## Same answer?
# all((covmat2 - covmat) == 0) # TRUE! - also no speed change
  1. generate \(\delta_i\) with rmvmnorm().
# Generate spatially correlated errors (delta) ----
del = mvtnorm::rmvnorm(n = ntime, sigma = covmat, method = "chol")
  1. generate \(\varepsilon_{i}(t)\).
# Generate ARMA errors (epsilon) ----
## apply arima.sim() to each column of del
eps = t(apply(X = del, MARGIN = 2, 
             function(e){
               arima.sim(n = ntime, 
                         model = list(ar = rhos, ma = thetas), 
                         innov = e)
             }))

end.time = Sys.time()
end.time - start.time # 3.42 minutes
## Time difference of 0.7662461 secs

Let’s visualize the correlations among \(\varepsilon_{i}(t)\) in space and time:

  1. Add the errors to the rest of the sim model
# beta, phi, gamma: user defined effects parameters (possibly spatially variable)
# u: spatially generated predictors (via mattern function)
# m: spatio-temporally generated predictors (mattern & ARMA functions)

x = beta*u +  phi*u*time  + gamma*w + eps 

#Note: proper matrix multiplication will be used

Spatially variability: Matern Covariance

To demonstrate how we can simulate a waved spatial pattern in our predictors and effects parameters, I’ll now generate a spatially variable nugget using Matern cross-covariance. When \(v\) and \(c\) are both large, you get a wave across the map:

The Matern function is ideal for simulating spatial variables and spatial parameters because the resultant patterns can be substantially changed by varying \(v\) and \(c\). To demonstrate this, I’ll vary \(c\) and \(r\). \(c = {1/2, 1, 10, 20}\) and \(v = {1/2, 1, 2, 10}\)

whereas the stable exponential function has more limited range (\(0<a\leq2\)). Though, the Gaussian version (\(a = 2\)) can generate interesting and realistic patterns:

r.tmp = c(.05, 0.2, .5, 1)*map.cols

a.tmp = c(.5, 1, 1.5, 2)

spatcor.tab = data.frame(NULL)

for (a in a.tmp) for (r in r.tmp){
  
  nugpars = list(scale = r, power = a, 
               mean = 0, sill = 1, nugget = 0)
  
  nug.vcov = CompRandFld::Covmatrix(coords, 
                                    distance = dist.meth, 
                                    corrmodel = "stable", 
                                    param = nugpars)$covmatrix
  # image(nug.vcov)
  spat.nug <- scales::rescale(mvtnorm::rmvnorm(n = 1, sigma = nug.vcov), to = constrain.nug)
  tmp = data.frame(coords, nug = as.vector(spat.nug), r = r/map.cols, a = a)
  spatcor.tab = rbind(spatcor.tab, tmp)
  
  # nug.corpars = list(scale = range, power = a, sill = psill, nugget = 0, mean = 0)
  # covmat = CompRandFld::Covmatrix(coordx = coords, 
  #                                 distance = dist.meth,
  #                                 corrmodel = cormod,
  #                                 param = nug.corpars)$covmatrix
  # 
  # covmat = diag(as.vector(spat.nug)) + (1-mean(as.vector(spat.nug)))*covmat
  # del = mvtnorm::rmvnorm(n = ntime, sigma = covmat, method = "chol")
  # eps = t(apply(X = del, MARGIN = 2, 
  #               function(e){
  #                 arima.sim(n = ntime, 
  #                           model = list(ar = rhos, ma = thetas), 
  #                           innov = e)
  #               }))
  
}

ggplot(data = spatcor.tab, aes(x = x, y = y, fill = nug)) +
  theme_classic() + 
  theme(legend.position = "none",
        panel.spacing = unit(0, "lines")) +
  geom_tile() + 
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "magma") +
  facet_grid(r ~ a, labeller = "label_both") +
  labs(x = "x coord", y = "y coord", title = "spatial patterns (stable exp covariance)")

The matern covariance structure seems to have been developed to generate more bioligically realistic spatial patterns.
